Okay so this PR ended up being much more than what it was originally expected to be lol.

Here is the list of the changes:

* Sprites are now centered around their transform. Changed accordingly in the pong example.
* Begin the work on #1053 by removing GlobalTransform from the pong example. 
* Special format to load Ron files containing a custom spritesheet. Example:

```
(
    spritesheet_width: 8.0,
    spritesheet_height: 16.0,
    sprites: [
        (
            x: 0.0,
            y: 0.0,
            width: 4.0,
            height: 16.0,
        ),
        (
            x: 4.0,
            y: 0.0,
            width: 4.0,
            height: 4.0,
        ),
    ],
)
```

It takes as a parameter the texture ID of the texture associated to the spritesheet, and outputs a SpriteSheet struct containing all the sprites.

```rust
let texture_handle = {
    let loader = world.read_resource::<Loader>();
    let texture_storage = world.read_resource::<AssetStorage<Texture>>();
    loader.load(
        "texture/tiles.png",
        PngFormat,
        Default::default(),
        (),
        &texture_storage,
    )
};

let mut material_texture_set = world.write_resource::<MaterialTextureSet>();
material_texture_set.insert(TEXTURE_ID, texture_handle);

let loader = world.read_resource::<Loader>();
let sprite_sheet_store = world.read_resource::<AssetStorage<SpriteSheet>>();
let sprite_sheet = loader.load(
    "texture/tiles.ron",
    SpriteSheetFormat,
    TEXTURE_ID,
    (),
    &sprite_sheet_store,
);
```
As you can see it is now very easy to load sprites.
* Added it to the pong tutorial, and extended the sprites guide to explain it.
